===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-bombard.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|bombarde||a bombard, mortar, catapult"; also "a bassoon-like musical instrument}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|bombus||buzzing; booming}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# a [[medieval]] primitive [[cannon]], used chiefly in [[siege]]s for throwing heavy stone balls.
#* Knolles
#*: They planted in divers places twelve great '''bombards''', wherewith they threw huge stones into the air, which, falling down into the city, might break down the houses.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} a [[bassoon]]-like medieval instrument
# {{label|en|obsolete}} a large liquor container made of [[leather]], in the form of a jug or a bottle.
#* '''1610''', ''[[s:The Tempest|The Tempest]]'', by [[w:William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]], act 2 scene 2
#*: {{...}} yond same black cloud, yond huge one, / looks like a foul '''bombard''' that would shed his liquor.
# {{label|en|poetic|rare}} A [[bombardment]].
#: {{rfquotek|J. Barlow}}
# {{label|en|music}} A [[bombardon]].

